# EU accessibility

The entire site must be accessible under the **European Accessibility Act** and **EN 301 549**, targeting **WCAG 2.1 Level AA**.

## Must have on every page

- Valid language (`lang` on `<html>`), semantic landmarks (`header`, `nav`, `main`, `footer`).
- Skip link to main content; visible when focused.
- Keyboard access for all interactive controls; no keyboard traps.
- Visible focus styles (never `outline: none` without a clear replacement).
- Text/UI contrast ≥ 4.5:1 (normal text) and ≥ 3:1 (large text / UI boundaries).
- Images: meaningful `alt`, or empty `alt=""` only when decorative beside adjacent text.
- Forms: visible labels (`for`/`id`), errors linked with `aria-describedby`, `aria-invalid` when wrong, useful `autocomplete`.
- Links/buttons: clear accessible name; external links that open a new tab say so.
- `prefers-reduced-motion`: no non-essential motion.
- Status messages: `role="status"` / `aria-live="polite"` (or assertive for errors).

## When changing UI

- Test with keyboard (Tab, Enter, Escape) and a screen-reader path for new flows.
- Do not rely on colour alone for meaning (errors, selected slots).
- Keep touch targets roughly ≥ 44×44 px where practical.
- Update the accessibility statement if you change major access features.

## Example

```html
<!-- ✅ GOOD -->
<label for="id_email">E-post</label>
<input id="id_email" type="email" autocomplete="email" required
       aria-invalid="true" aria-describedby="id_email_error">
<p id="id_email_error" class="field-error">Ange en giltig e-postadress.</p>

<!-- ❌ BAD -->
<input type="email" placeholder="E-post" style="outline:none">
```
